of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Alice de Rougham was born in 1285. She married John de Rougham about 1310, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Rougham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1285–":"1285–Surnud","1275–1316":"1275–1316","1316–Male":"1316–Surnud","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1316":"1316","ABT 1310":"umbes 1310","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","Abt 1316":"umbes 1316","Rougham, Mitford, Norfolk, England":"Rougham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rougham, , Norfolk, England":"Rougham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",",,England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1285–":"1285–Kuollut","1275–1316":"1275–1316","1316–Male":"1316–Kuollut","1285–Female":"1285–Kuollut","1316":"1316","ABT 1310":"noin 1310","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","Abt 1316":"noin 1316","Rougham, Mitford, Norfolk, England":"Rougham, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Rougham, , Norfolk, England":"Rougham, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta",",,England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1285–":"1285–Décédée","1275–1316":"1275–1316","1316–Male":"1316–Décédé","1285–Female":"1285–Décédée","1316":"1316","ABT 1310":"environ 1310","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","Abt 1316":"environ 1316","Rougham, Mitford, Norfolk, England":"Rougham, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Rougham, , Norfolk, England":"Rougham, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni",",,England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Alice de Rougham est née en 1285. Elle a épousé John de Rougham environ 1310, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est décédée à Rougham, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"1285–":"1285–Verstorben","1275–1316":"1275–1316","1316–Male":"1316–Verstorben","1285–Female":"1285–Verstorben","1316":"1316","ABT 1310":"um 1310","1275":"1275",